As the Taliban solidifies its hold over Afghanistan and the Biden administration works to quickly evacuate thousands of American citizens and Afghans, many in Washington are pointing fingers trying to decide who is to blame. 

National security reporter Alex Ward takes a closer look at how the blame game will play out.

https://politi.co/2W4DPQu

node.text:
A defiant President Biden on Monday said he did not regret his decision to withdraw American forces from Afghanistan, while acknowledging that the country's collapse to the Taliban came much sooner than U.S. officials had anticipated.

"I stand squarely behind my decision," he said from the White House. "The truth is this did unfold more quickly than we had anticipated.”

Watch highlights from Biden's speech in 180 seconds. https://politi.co/3xUft8E

node.text:
Time is not on Trump's side. The Biden administration saw a major win by passing a bipartisan trillion dollar infrastructure bill that could flood the workforce with thousands of jobs and keep his campaign promise to fix Washington. Since losing the 2020 election, the former president has had a handful of botched attempts to return to the spotlight. 

Ryan Lizza breaks down the dynamics of Trump's return, what's working, what isn't and what to expect next.

node.title: Trump's influence keeps haunting Washington, explained

node.text:
A year after New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo reached new political heights with daily news briefings that enraptured a nation in the throes of a once-in-a-lifetime pandemic, the three-term Democrat announced plans to resign amid growing pressure to leave or face impeachment over allegations that he sexually harassed nearly a dozen women.

“Given the circumstances, the best way I can help now is if I step aside and let the government get back to government,” Cuomo said in a video statement. “Therefore that's what I'll do, because I work for you, and doing the right thing, is doing the right thing for you. Because, as we say, ‘it's not about me, it's about we.’” 

Read more at the link in bio.

https://politi.co/2UaCHK6

node.title: Andrew Cuomo resigns amid sexual harassment scandal

node.text:
The U.S. evacuation mission in Afghanistan has come to an end, leaving behind Americans and thousands of Afghan allies.

The last C-17 departed from Hamid Karzai International airport on Monday, meeting President Joe Biden’s Aug. 31 deadline.

“Tonight's withdrawal signifies both the end of the military component of the evacuation but also the end of the nearly 20-year mission that began in Afghanistan shortly after Sept. 11, 2001,” said Gen. Kenneth McKenzie, commander of the U.S. Central Command. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
About 750,000 renter households will likely lose their homes this year after the Supreme Court blocked the federal eviction moratorium.

Tenants owe between $12 billion and $17 billion to landlords as Covid-19 cases surge and about 2.5 million to 3.5 million households are behind on rent, according to Goldman Sachs economists.

The findings mark one of the first comprehensive estimates of what could happen in the absence of the eviction ban. The ban was stopped as state and local governments continued to experience bottlenecks in the delivery of $46.5 billion in federal rental assistance. 

Given the slow pace of rental aid disbursement, Goldman's analysts expect that between 1 million and 2 million households will remain without support and at risk of eviction when the remaining state and local eviction bans expire at the end of September. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
Exclusive: Just 24 hours before a suicide bomber set off an explosive outside the Kabul Airport that killed almost 200 people, senior military leaders gathered for the Pentagon’s daily morning update on the deteriorating situation in Afghanistan. According to classified detailed notes of the gathering shared with us:

➡️ Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin instructed more than a dozen top leaders to make preparations for an imminent “mass casualty event.” 
➡️ Gen. Mark Milley warned of “significant” intelligence indicating that the Islamic State’s Afghanistan affiliate, ISIS-K, was planning a “complex attack.”
➡️ Commanders calling in from Kabul said that the Abbey Gate, where American citizens had been told to gather in order to gain entrance to the airport, was “highest risk,” and detailed their plans to protect the airport.
➡️ “I don’t believe people get the incredible amount of risk on the ground,” Austin said, according to the classified notes.

Our exclusive story takes you inside the Pentagon: what intel they had, the fateful decision to keep the airport gate open and their deepening frustration with reliance on the Taliban to provide security in Kabul. Link in bio to read.

node.text:
Florida is starting to turn on Gov. Ron DeSantis. For the past year he's been a rising GOP star, an heir apparent to Trump – but the latest Covid surge is starting to change that. 

Covid infection rates continue to climb in Florida as the state faces shortages of health care workers, morgue space and even oxygen for patients. About 16,000 people are hospitalized. Child infection rates have shot up. School districts have rebelled against his anti-mask mandates. Cruise lines are resisting his vaccine passport ban. Even his recent poll numbers are slipping.

DeSantis still remains popular with conservatives, but his refusal to implement Covid-related restrictions as the virus continues to infect and kill Floridians could threaten his electability.

“You can tout all the freedom and anti-lockdown that you want,” one GOP consultant told us. “There’s no political strategy for sick kids and tired parents.”

Link in bio for the full story.

node.text:
As expected, the Supreme Court blocked Biden's new eviction ban last night. (If you saw our IG Story a few weeks ago, you'll know why – it's highlighted on our profile.) Now Dems are scrambling to figure out how to protect millions of renters who face eviction. 

The issue is now back on Congress's plate, and House Dems say they’re considering “possible legislative remedies” to revive the ban. But it looks unlikely they’ll be able to rally enough support. The Biden administration imposed the moratorium earlier this month — after first citing concerns about its legality — because House Dems were unable to drum up the votes to put the policy into law. 

"If there were enough votes to pass an eviction moratorium in Congress it would have happened,” said White House spokesperson Jen Psaki. “It hasn't happened."

Link in bio for the full story.

Now, as the vice president grapples with some of the thorniest issues in politics and builds relationships with a wide array of Democrats — which she could leverage in both the administration and a future presidential campaign — even some of her closest allies admit she needs help fending off incoming fire.

We dug into Harris' law school years, her performance eight months into the vice presidency and how wearing the mantle of “first” comes layered with racism and misogyny.

This was exactly the kind of situation Biden was hoping to avoid by leaving Afghanistan. Now at least 13 U.S. troops and 95 Afghans are dead after an ISIS suicide bomb – the deadliest attack on American forces in Afghanistan in a decade.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The tragedy in Kabul will be a part of Biden's legacy – and it also has the makings of a growing crisis that threatens him in several ways:
➡️ Congressional Republicans are up in arms, saying none of this had to happen. There's already calls for him to resign and talk of future impeachment.
➡️ Some Dems on the Hill are now trying to distance themselves from Biden. He used to be seen as key to helping them win competitive swing seats.
➡️ There’s growing outrage over U.S. officials giving the Taliban a list of Americans and Afghan allies to evacuate, despite the Taliban's history of brutally murdering our Afghan allies. We were the first to report this yesterday.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

If $3.5 trillion of social spending sounds like a lot, Bernie Sanders wants to convince you (and his fellow Congress members) that it's the investment America needs.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
If it passes, the historic spending plan would lead to the largest federal expansions of benefit programs ever, including expanding health care coverage, taking climate action and increasing access to education. It would be paid for by raising taxes on corporations and the wealthy.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
While Sanders and most Dems believe the $3.5T number is indispensable, it's unclear whether the plan can get through both the House (where Dems only have a slim majority) and the Senate (where they're evenly split). The most obvious obstacles are moderate Dem senators Kyrsten Sinema and Joe Manchin (they’re worried about the effect on inflation), along with softer dissent among a few other centrists.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
So now Sanders is going all out to protect the spending plan and boost public support for it. He’s traveling to Iowa, Indiana and Michigan for events and says the $3.5 trillion top line number is “non-negotiable.”
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
“This is, in my view, the minimum of what we should be spending,” Sanders told us.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Link in bio for more from our interview with Sanders.

node.text:
ISIS militants attacked the crowds of people trying to get out of Afghanistan today, killing at least 13 U.S. troops and 95 Afghans at the Kabul airport and injuring many more, according to U.S. and Afghan officials. (Note that these numbers are in flux and could increase. We’ve updated this caption since posting it.)

The militants set off a bomb outside the airport where thousands of people have been gathering amid the massive evacuation effort. ISIS gunmen also opened fire on the crowd, prompting U.S. troops to return fire, sources said. 

This is the deadliest U.S. casualty event in Afghanistan since 2011, and it happened just days before a complete U.S. withdrawal from a country now controlled by the Taliban. It also came just hours after defense officials started warning about an increased ISIS threat at the Kabul airport. We were the first to report about those warnings yesterday.

Deep blue California is closer to having a Republican governor than anyone thought, according to the latest polling. The recall stands within a few percentage points of passing next month – a once-unthinkably close margin that's almost entirely due to lukewarm Democratic interest in the race. 

As the Sept. 14 election date gets closer, Gov. Gavin Newsom (pictured) is now pointing to Florida as the ultimate threat of what California could become if a Republican takes over. Meanwhile, conservatives have repeatedly said that's something to aspire to: They're fighting to replace Newsom and his public health orders with someone more like mask-averse Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis.

But despite the back and forth, it's not *really* about Florida. It's about who the state and its political leaders remind California of. Link in bio for the full story.
